  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="13" relname="concession">Induction is always permissible,</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="13" relname="span"> but the credibility of the induced general law depends on its scope S:</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="16" relname="condition"> the further S reaches into the future,</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="11" relname="span"> the less we trust the law.</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="8" relname="span"> So, there is a credibility of an induced ‘general law’</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="26" relname="span"> – and in addition this credibility is affected by further evidence.</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="12" relname="span"> 

The law will gain credit </segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="10" relname="disjunction">
if the person under consideration has not just survived a heart transplantation and is not nursed in an intensive care unit </segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="10" relname="disjunction">
or if he does not live in a country at war.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="24" relname="conjunction">
But even if all those circumstances are in favor of the person</segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="24" relname="conjunction"> and we limit the duration of the scope S of the law to say, a second, </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="21" relname="span">
the law may become extremely credible, </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="20" relname="span">
but it may still be false, </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="nonvolitional-cause">
because the person may die just at that very moment.
</segment>
